<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="u4-orthogonality-least-squares" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Orthogonality and least squares</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Orthogonality turns geometry into computation. In this unit, projection becomes the mechanism for best approximation, and regression becomes a linear algebra problem.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Big question.</em> When <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has no solution, what is the best approximate solution?
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Learning outcomes.</em> By the end of this unit, students should be able to:
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Core outcomes.</em>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>U4-LO1.</em> Use orthogonality and orthonormal bases to decompose vectors and compute coefficients.</li>
      <li><em>U4-LO2.</em> Construct orthogonal and orthonormal bases using Gram-Schmidt, and compute orthogonal complements.</li>
      <li><em>U4-LO3.</em> Compute orthogonal projections onto subspaces and solve closest-point problems.</li>
      <li><em>U4-LO4.</em> Formulate least squares as projection onto a column space, identify the residual, and explain residual orthogonality.</li>
      <li><em>U4-LO5.</em> Derive and solve the normal equations <m>A^TA\hat{\mathbf{x}}=A^T\mathbf{b}</m>, and use them in small regression problems.</li>
      <li><em>U4-LO6.</em> Compute and interpret QR factorizations, and use QR to solve linear systems and least-squares problems.</li>
      <li><em>U4-LO7.</em> Interpret computational least-squares checks such as <c>A.T @ r</c> and explain what they do and do not prove.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <em>Toolbox skills.</em> Compute dot products, test orthogonality, normalize vectors, apply Gram-Schmidt, compute projections, identify residuals, derive and solve normal equations, fit a line by least squares, check <m>A^T\mathbf{r}\approx \mathbf{0}</m>, and use QR in small least-squares problems.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Application and computation outcomes.</em> Interpret Lab U4 <c>[U4-LO4, U4-LO5, U4-LO7 | C+M+T | Core]</c> by reading projection computations, design matrices, least-squares coefficients, residual orthogonality, normal equations, QR checks, and code outputs such as <c>A.T @ r</c>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <xi:include href="sec-u4-orthogonality.ptx" />
  <xi:include href="sec-u4-orthogonal-complements-projections.ptx" />

  <section xml:id="sec-u4-least-squares-as-projection">
    <title>Least squares as projection</title>

    <p>
      Least squares is projection when the subspace is <m>\operatorname{col}(A)</m>.
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="sec-projection-as-optimization">
    <title>Projection as an optimization problem</title>
    <p>
      Orthogonal projection can also be read as an optimization problem. Given a subspace <m>U\subseteq \mathbb R^n</m> and a vector <m>\mathbf{x}_0</m>, the projection <m>\operatorname{proj}_U(\mathbf{x}_0)</m> is the vector <m>\mathbf{x}^*\in U</m> that minimizes <m>\|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}_0\|</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is the first version of a pattern that will recur in Units 5 and 7: choose a space of allowable approximations, choose a way to measure error, and find the point in the allowable space with smallest error.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="sec-least-squares-projection">
    <title>Least squares as projection</title>
    <p>
      The equation <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> may have no solution because <m>\mathbf{b}\notin\operatorname{col}(A)</m>. The least-squares problem asks for <m>\mathbf{x}</m> so that <m>A\mathbf{x}</m> is as close as possible to <m>\mathbf{b}</m>:
      <me>\min_{\mathbf{x}}\|A\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{b}\|.</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Unit 2 asked whether a target vector was reachable. Least squares asks for the closest reachable output when the target is not reachable.
    </p>
    <note xml:id="note-col-null-orthogonal-complement">
      <title>Column spaces and null spaces</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m\times n</m> matrix with columns <m>\mathbf{a}_1,\ldots,\mathbf{a}_n</m>. Then
        <me>\operatorname{col}(A)^\perp=\operatorname{null}(A^T).</me>
        Indeed, a vector <m>\mathbf{r}</m> is in <m>\operatorname{col}(A)^\perp</m> exactly when it is orthogonal to every column of <m>A</m>. That means
        <me>\mathbf{a}_1\cdot \mathbf{r}=0,\ldots,\mathbf{a}_n\cdot \mathbf{r}=0,</me>
        which is exactly the matrix equation <m>A^T\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{0}</m>.
      </p>
    </note>
    <p>
      Geometrically, <m>A\mathbf{x}</m> is a point in <m>\operatorname{col}(A)</m>. Thus the best possible <m>A\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> is the projection of <m>\mathbf{b}</m> onto the column space:
      <me>A\hat{\mathbf{x}}=\operatorname{proj}_{\operatorname{col}(A)}(\mathbf{b}).</me>
      The residual <m>\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{b}-A\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> is orthogonal to every column of <m>A</m>. Equivalently,
      <m>\mathbf{r}\in\operatorname{col}(A)^\perp=\operatorname{null}(A^T)</m>, so
      <me>A^T(\mathbf{b}-A\hat{\mathbf{x}})=\mathbf{0},\qquad A^TA\hat{\mathbf{x}}=A^T\mathbf{b}.</me>
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-normal-equations-residual-orthogonality">
      <title>Normal equations from residual orthogonality</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> minimizes <m>\|A\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{b}\|</m>, then the residual <m>\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{b}-A\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> is orthogonal to <m>\operatorname{col}(A)</m>. Equivalently, <m>\mathbf{r}\in\operatorname{col}(A)^\perp=\operatorname{null}(A^T)</m>, so
          <me>A^T(\mathbf{b}-A\hat{\mathbf{x}})=\mathbf{0},</me>
          and every least-squares solution satisfies the normal equations
          <me>A^TA\hat{\mathbf{x}}=A^T\mathbf{b}.</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      The closest point <m>A\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> in <m>\operatorname{col}(A)</m> is unique. The coefficient vector <m>\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> is unique when the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent. If the columns are dependent, several different coefficient vectors may produce the same closest point.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act-u4-ata-invertible-independent-columns">
      <title>Why <m>A^TA</m> is invertible for independent columns</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m\times n</m> matrix. Prove that <m>A</m> has linearly independent columns if and only if <m>A^T A</m> is invertible.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Suppose that the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent. To show that <m>A^T A</m> is invertible, it is enough to show that <m>(A^T A)\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m> has only the trivial solution. If <m>(A^T A)\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m>, then
          <me>
            0=\mathbf{x}^T(A^T A)\mathbf{x}=(A\mathbf{x})^T(A\mathbf{x})=\|A\mathbf{x}\|^2.
          </me>
          Therefore <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m>. Since the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent, <m>\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m>. Hence <m>A^T A</m> is invertible.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, suppose that <m>A^T A</m> is invertible and <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m>. Then
          <me>A^T A\mathbf{x}=A^T\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}.</me>
          Since <m>A^T A</m> is invertible, <m>\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m>. Therefore the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity xml:id="act-u4-unit2-target-revisited">
      <title>Unit 2 target revisited</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
          <me>
            A=\begin{bmatrix}1&amp;0\\0&amp;1\\1&amp;1\end{bmatrix},
            \qquad
            \mathbf{b}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\4\end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>Explain why <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has no solution.</p></li>
          <li><p>Form <m>A^TA</m> and <m>A^T\mathbf{b}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Solve the normal equations.</p></li>
          <li><p>Compute <m>A\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m> and <m>\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{b}-A\hat{\mathbf{x}}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Check <m>A^T\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{0}</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If <m>\mathbf{x}=\begin{bmatrix}x_1\\x_2\end{bmatrix}</m>, then
          <me>
            A\mathbf{x}
            =
            \begin{bmatrix}x_1\\x_2\\x_1+x_2\end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          The first two coordinates of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> force <m>x_1=1</m> and <m>x_2=2</m>, but then the third coordinate would be <m>3</m>, not <m>4</m>. So the target is not reached exactly.
        </p>
        <p>
          The normal equations use
          <me>
            A^TA=\begin{bmatrix}2&amp;1\\1&amp;2\end{bmatrix},
            \qquad
            A^T\mathbf{b}=\begin{bmatrix}5\\6\end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          Solving
          <me>
            \begin{bmatrix}2&amp;1\\1&amp;2\end{bmatrix}\hat{\mathbf{x}}
            =
            \begin{bmatrix}5\\6\end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          gives
          <me>
            \hat{\mathbf{x}}=\begin{bmatrix}4/3\\7/3\end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore
          <me>
            A\hat{\mathbf{x}}
            =
            \begin{bmatrix}4/3\\7/3\\11/3\end{bmatrix},
            \qquad
            \mathbf{r}
            =
            \mathbf{b}-A\hat{\mathbf{x}}
            =
            \begin{bmatrix}-1/3\\-1/3\\1/3\end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          Finally,
          <me>
            A^T\mathbf{r}
            =
            \begin{bmatrix}1&amp;0&amp;1\\0&amp;1&amp;1\end{bmatrix}
            \begin{bmatrix}-1/3\\-1/3\\1/3\end{bmatrix}
            =
            \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          The residual is not zero, so the target is still not reached exactly. But the residual is orthogonal to the column space, so the fitted output is the closest reachable output.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="ex-regression-three-points">
    <title>Regression example</title>
    <p>
      Fit <m>y=c_0+c_1t</m> to <m>(0,1)</m>, <m>(1,2)</m>, and <m>(2,2)</m>. Then
      <me>A=\begin{bmatrix}1&amp;0\\1&amp;1\\1&amp;2\end{bmatrix},\qquad \mathbf{b}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\2\end{bmatrix}.</me>
      The normal equations are <m>A^TA\mathbf{c}=A^T\mathbf{b}</m>. Since
      <me>A^TA=\begin{bmatrix}3&amp;3\\3&amp;5\end{bmatrix},\qquad A^T\mathbf{b}=\begin{bmatrix}5\\6\end{bmatrix},</me>
      we get <m>c_0=7/6</m> and <m>c_1=1/2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The fitted line is <m>y=7/6+(1/2)t</m>. The fitted values are
      <me>A\mathbf{c}=\begin{bmatrix}7/6\\5/3\\13/6\end{bmatrix},</me>
      so the residual is
      <me>\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{b}-A\mathbf{c}=\begin{bmatrix}-1/6\\1/3\\-1/6\end{bmatrix}.</me>
      Check the orthogonality condition:
      <me>A^T\mathbf{r}=
      \begin{bmatrix}1&amp;1&amp;1\\0&amp;1&amp;2\end{bmatrix}
      \begin{bmatrix}-1/6\\1/3\\-1/6\end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="sec-u4-apps-computation">
    <title>Code snapshot: fitting and checking the residual</title>
    <p xml:id="sec-u4-code-residual">
      <em>Code snapshot: fitting and checking the residual</em>
    </p>
    <program language="python"><code><![CDATA[xhat = np.linalg.lstsq(A, b, rcond=None)[0]
r = b - A @ xhat
A.T @ r
]]></code></program>
    <p>
      The vector <m>\mathbf{r}</m> is the residual. The output of <c>A.T @ r</c> should be close to zero because the least-squares residual is orthogonal to the columns of <m>A</m>.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <p>
    QR will compute the same least-squares solution without directly forming <m>A^TA</m>.
  </p>
  </section>

  <xi:include href="sec-u4-qr-factorization.ptx" />

  <section xml:id="sec-u4-applications-computation-recap">
    <title>Applications and computation recap</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        This section checks whether you can read the computations already used in Unit 4.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-u4-review-checkpoints">
      <title>Review checkpoints</title>
      <activity xml:id="act-u4-recap-residual-orthogonality">
        <title>Checkpoint: reading residual orthogonality</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <c>A.T @ r</c> is nearly zero, what geometric condition has been checked? Does this mean <m>\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{0}</m>?
          </p>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U4-LO4, U4-LO7 | C+T | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </activity>
      <activity xml:id="act-u4-recap-near-zero-residual-output">
        <title>Checkpoint: interpreting a near-zero <m>A^T\mathbf{r}</m> output</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A computation gives <m>A^T\mathbf{r}=(0.000001,-0.000003)</m>. What geometric condition is being checked? Does it mean the residual vector is zero?
          </p>
          <p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U4-LO4, U4-LO7 | C+T | Core]</c></p>
        </statement>
      </activity>
      <p>
        <em>Exam skill.</em> Given a design matrix and residual output, explain projection onto the column space without solving a full regression problem by hand. <em>Tags.</em> <c>[U4-LO4, U4-LO5, U4-LO7 | C+M+T | Core]</c>
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="lab-u4-callout">
      <title>Linked notebook</title>
      <p>
        <url href="https://sebroc.github.io/MATH345-Course-Materials/labs/#lab-u4">Run Lab U4: Regression as projection</url>. Focus on the design matrix, fitted coefficients, residual, and the computation <c>A.T @ r</c>.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <conclusion>
      <p>
        For a quick reference on least-squares commands, transposes, matrix products, and numerical checks such as "close to zero," see the programming appendix sections <xref ref="appcomp-numpy-linalg" text="global"/>, <xref ref="appcomp-elementwise-vs-linear-algebra" text="global"/>, and <xref ref="appcomp-numerical-checks" text="global"/>.
      </p>
    </conclusion>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="u4-exercises">
    <title>Exercises</title>
